Is Europe's elite ready for trade with Britain?
The Business for Britain campaign (commerce for Britain) was launched in April with the promise to bring together businesses and define what changes in the relationship with the EU that British entrepreneurs and job-creating companies want to see.
To this end, we commissioned the largest and most comprehensive survey, in which we asked the leading British businessmen about their views on Britain, trade and the EU.
YouGov interviewed 1,000 business leaders representing British businesses of various sizes and from different sectors and regions.
The survey results will come as a surprise to many.
We found that the vast majority of businesses are now trying to export outside Europe and are focusing on countries that are modernising and growing, while EU states are stagnating.
They want to see the government's preference for new trade ties with countries such as China, India and Brazil, rather than get bogged down in a long and arduous process of reforming mysterious European institutions.
When we asked for their views on specific policy areas – from monopoly regulations to product laws – most entrepreneurs expressed the view that control of these key competences should return to Westminster.
There was general dissatisfaction with the single market, and entrepreneurs said that the costs of Brussels' regulations were now outweighed by the benefits of being part of the European trade area - even 40 per cent of the large companies, the most pro-European companies, had even expressed their consent.
Finally, our business leaders survey revealed the most telling knowledge, that a clear majority wants Britain to seek to amend the treaty and the relationship with the EU, which should be based on trade, not policy.
The findings with which businesses of different sizes and the main business groups have endorsed show that the business sector is pushing for a "meaningful change" that will take back the influence back on Britain.
There is a lot at stake – reaching a treaty change and a better agreement for Britain can mean a gain of up to 16% in the vote in the referendum to remain in the EU.
The Prime Minister should not hesitate: this survey shows that British trade supports his plan to amend the terms of British EU membership.
This also shows that the business sector expects this amendment to mark a significant shift from the current rebalancing of forces towards Britain.
A better deal for Britain is possible, and increasingly necessary, given the eurozone's path as a closer economic and fiscal union.
