I'm reading a very sad book these days.
I thought of this book that during the grim days of my second year at the medical school, I would be encouraged and renewed for me in a chore of hope.
It's called "The Audacity to Win" and these are memories of Barack Obama's presidential campaign in 2008.
When I finish the patient reviews in the evening and go to bed, the book takes me back to a time when politics inspired millions of people and your speeches took your breath away.
The election ended in overwhelmingly dominance, and the TV news was forcing us to reflect on the historical value of this moment.
My classmates were crying with joy, and my parents kept the paper they could get.
A young visionary team headed to the White House and the nation was ready for change.
During his inauguration in 2008, Obama had 82 percent of support.
And this is where I'm closing the book.
Going to the present is a harsh awakening, like waking up from a dream.
It is hard to recall these optimistic days - seem to be a distant memory, a sad reminder of missed opportunities.
Indeed, in the years after I threw in my first ballot, there were indeed changes.
It was certainly none of the most I had imagined.
I recognize that Obama has achieved a number of great and diverse achievements – from the Affordable Care Act to the removal of our troops from Iraq and the end of the "no question, say nothing" policy after the killing of Osama bin Laden.
Moreover, I believe that the party's obstruction has reversed so much effort to move our nation forward: among other things, it is immigration reform, the public's ability to choose health care and close the Guantánamo base.
But after many of the situations in which I defended the Obama administration from my colleagues and comrades, I have reached an absolute limit when it comes to the explanations they can provide.
I found myself in a place of political hopelessness.
Republicans' obstruction cannot explain the approval of foreign leaders' eavesdropping or the drone raids that kill innocent children overseas.
It cannot be explained by them that the National Security Agency is collecting data about the private lives of Americans, or of pursuing those who detect the government's mishandling.
They cannot be held responsible for the execution of Anwar al-Awlaki, an American citizen, without a proper trial, or a curtailment of public contributions and expenses during the presidential campaigns.
It is impossible to justify the findings of the report, which says that the White House's efforts to silence the media are "most aggressive ... from the Nixon administration."
And most recently, they can't even excuse the inability to create a simple website more than 3 years after the Consignation of the Affordable Care Act.
I don't know if such a thing was to be expected.
Whether I should have known at the age of 18 that government power could be at odds with the political campaigns that preceded it.
The election position clearly does not have a predictable course, and our public talks will be shaped by the opposition political party and random events such as the Newton massacre.
However, all the examples I have given above seem to the extent to be the result of the administration's own decision.
And that's what worries me the most.
I voted for Obama again in 2012, but not because I was excited about his candidacy.
Mitt Romney was a plight and unpubtened alternative, and he seemed unable to consolidate his policy or position.
I felt that a second term for Obama, freed from the pressure of the next election, would live up to the hopes we had once heard of.
Yet a return to 2008 – with Obama's support to fall below 45% this week – is getting harder and harder through this book.
It makes me remember that series of promises that have faded.
This week, I read a chapter in the book about how Obama suffered a crushing defeat to Clinton in the New Yorkonist primary.
At the next meeting during the campaign, he told his staff that he had to get back up to speed and remain loyal to his mission.
"I want our charm back," he said.
We must remember who we are.
Five years have passed, Mr. President, and I agree with you.
