The bill's approval comes amid a series of measures to strengthen national security immediately after the Islamic gunman's attack at the Westgate shopping centre in September.
The authorities' anger was approached by the Kenyan media when it aired a security camera footage of the military's senters allegedly looting a luxury goods store on the scene of the attack.
The police director responded by having two journalists and a head of a media officer be called in for questioning, but the summons were later withdrawn after pressure from the media.
Under the new bill, media companies can be fined up to 20 million by Kenyan shillings and individual journalists up to one million, along with the risk of "assignment on the list" or be denied official journalistic accreditation.
